The paper discusses a technique for similarity search in high-dimensional spaces, which is a common problem in several areas of computer science. The use of locality-sensitive hashing (LSH) is a well-established approach for this problem, and the paper proposes a new LSH scheme called Fast CoveringLSH (fcLSH) that improves on previous methods. This makes the paper relevant to several subfields of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), information retrieval (cs.IR), computer vision (cs.CV), machine learning (cs.LG), and databases (cs.DB). Among these, data structures and information retrieval are the most likely categories, as they are directly related to the problem of similarity search. Computer vision is also a possibility, as similarity search is a common task in image and video analysis. Machine learning and databases are less likely, but still possible, as they both involve working with high-dimensional data.
